Here is a complete, well-typed Binary Search Tree implementation in TypeScript:

```typescript
// ============================================================
// Type Definitions
// ============================================================

interface BSTNode<T> {
  value: T;
  left: BSTNode<T> | null;
  right: BSTNode<T> | null;
}

type Comparator<T> = (a: T, b: T) => number;

// ============================================================
// Node Factory
// ============================================================

function createNode<T>(value: T): BSTNode<T> {
  return { value, left: null, right: null };
}

// ============================================================
// Binary Search Tree Class
// ============================================================

class BinarySearchTree<T> {
  private root: BSTNode<T> | null = null;
  private comparator: Comparator<T>;

  /**
   * @param comparator - Optional custom comparator function.
   * Defaults to natural (ascending) ordering for numbers and strings.
   * Return negative if a < b, 0 if a === b, positive if a > b.
   */
  constructor(comparator?: Comparator<T>) {
    this.comparator =
      comparator ??
      ((a, b) => {
        if (a < b) return -1;
        if (a > b) return 1;
        return 0;
      });
  }

  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // INSERT
  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  /**
   * Inserts a value into the BST. Duplicate values are ignored.
   * Time complexity: O(h), where h is the height of the tree.
   */
  insert(value: T): this {
    this.root = this._insertNode(this.root, value);
    return this; // enables chaining: bst.insert(1).insert(2)
  }

  private _insertNode(node: BSTNode<T> | null, value: T): BSTNode<T> {
    if (node === null) return createNode(value);

    const cmp = this.comparator(value, node.value);

    if (cmp < 0) {
      node.left = this._insertNode(node.left, value);
    } else if (cmp > 0) {
      node.right = this._insertNode(node.right, value);
    }
    // cmp === 0: duplicate — do nothing

    return node;
  }

  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // SEARCH
  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  /**
   * Searches for a value in the BST.
   * Returns the matching node, or null if not found.
   * Time complexity: O(h)
   */
  search(value: T): BSTNode<T> | null {
    return this._searchNode(this.root, value);
  }

  /** Convenience method — returns true/false instead of the node. */
  contains(value: T): boolean {
    return this.search(value) !== null;
  }

  private _searchNode(
    node: BSTNode<T> | null,
    value: T
  ): BSTNode<T> | null {
    if (node === null) return null;

    const cmp = this.comparator(value, node.value);

    if (cmp < 0) return this._searchNode(node.left, value);
    if (cmp > 0) return this._searchNode(node.right, value);
    return node; // found
  }

  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // DELETE
  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  /**
   * Removes a value from the BST (if it exists).
   * Uses the in-order successor strategy for nodes with two children.
   * Time complexity: O(h)
   */
  delete(value: T): this {
    this.root = this._deleteNode(this.root, value);
    return this;
  }

  private _deleteNode(
    node: BSTNode<T> | null,
    value: T
  ): BSTNode<T> | null {
    if (node === null) return null; // value not found — no-op

    const cmp = this.comparator(value, node.value);

    if (cmp < 0) {
      node.left = this._deleteNode(node.left, value);
    } else if (cmp > 0) {
      node.right = this._deleteNode(node.right, value);
    } else {
      // Node to delete found — three cases:

      // Case 1: Leaf node (no children)
      if (node.left === null && node.right === null) {
        return null;
      }

      // Case 2: One child — replace node with its child
      if (node.left === null) return node.right;
      if (node.right === null) return node.left;

      // Case 3: Two children — replace value with in-order successor
      // (smallest value in the right subtree), then delete the successor.
      const successor = this._findMin(node.right);
      node.value = successor.value;
      node.right = this._deleteNode(node.right, successor.value);
    }

    return node;
  }

  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // TRAVERSALS
  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  /**
   * In-order traversal (Left → Root → Right).
   * Visits nodes in ascending sorted order.
   * Time complexity: O(n)
   */
  inorder(): T[] {
    const result: T[] = [];
    this._inorderTraverse(this.root, result);
    return result;
  }

  private _inorderTraverse(node: BSTNode<T> | null, result: T[]): void {
    if (node === null) return;
    this._inorderTraverse(node.left, result);
    result.push(node.value);
    this._inorderTraverse(node.right, result);
  }

  /**
   * Pre-order traversal (Root → Left → Right).
   * Useful for serializing/copying the tree structure.
   * Time complexity: O(n)
   */
  preorder(): T[] {
    const result: T[] = [];
    this._preorderTraverse(this.root, result);
    return result;
  }

  private _preorderTraverse(node: BSTNode<T> | null, result: T[]): void {
    if (node === null) return;
    result.push(node.value);
    this._preorderTraverse(node.left, result);
    this._preorderTraverse(node.right, result);
  }

  /**
   * Post-order traversal (Left → Right → Root).
   * Useful for deleting or evaluating the entire tree.
   * Time complexity: O(n)
   */
  postorder(): T[] {
    const result: T[] = [];
    this._postorderTraverse(this.root, result);
    return result;
  }

  private _postorderTraverse(node: BSTNode<T> | null, result: T[]): void {
    if (node === null) return;
    this._postorderTraverse(node.left, result);
    this._postorderTraverse(node.right, result);
    result.push(node.value);
  }

  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  // UTILITY METHODS
  // ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  /** Returns the node with the minimum value in the tree (or subtree). */
  findMin(): BSTNode<T> | null {
    if (this.root === null) return null;
    return this._findMin(this.root);
  }

  private _findMin(node: BSTNode<T>): BSTNode<T> {
    return node.left === null ? node : this._findMin(node.left);
  }

  /** Returns the node with the maximum value in the tree (or subtree). */
  findMax(): BSTNode<T> | null {
    if (this.root === null) return null;
    return this._findMax(this.root);
  }

  private _findMax(node: BSTNode<T>): BSTNode<T> {
    return node.right === null ? node : this._findMax(node.right);
  }

  /** Returns the height of the tree. An empty tree has height -1. */
  height(): number {
    return this._calcHeight(this.root);
  }

  private _calcHeight(node: BSTNode<T> | null): number {
    if (node === null) return -1;
    return 1 + Math.max(this._calcHeight(node.left), this._calcHeight(node.right));
  }

  /** Returns the total number of nodes. */
  size(): number {
    return this._countNodes(this.root);
  }

  private _countNodes(node: BSTNode<T> | null): number {
    if (node === null) return 0;
    return 1 + this._countNodes(node.left) + this._countNodes(node.right);
  }

  /** Removes all nodes from the tree. */
  clear(): void {
    this.root = null;
  }

  /** Returns true if the tree is empty. */
  isEmpty(): boolean {
    return this.root === null;
  }
}

// ============================================================
// Usage Examples
// ============================================================

// --- Numeric BST ---
const numTree = new BinarySearchTree<number>();

numTree.insert(10).insert(5).insert(15).insert(3).insert(7).insert(12).insert(18);
//         10
//        /  \
//       5    15
//      / \  /  \
//     3   7 12  18

console.log("Inorder:  ", numTree.inorder());   // [3, 5, 7, 10, 12, 15, 18]
console.log("Preorder: ", numTree.preorder());  // [10, 5, 3, 7, 15, 12, 18]
console.log("Postorder:", numTree.postorder()); // [3, 7, 5, 12, 18, 15, 10]

console.log("Contains 7:",  numTree.contains(7));   // true
console.log("Contains 99:", numTree.contains(99));  // false
console.log("Search 15:",   numTree.search(15));    // { value: 15, left: {...}, right: {...} }

console.log("Min:", numTree.findMin()?.value); // 3
console.log("Max:", numTree.findMax()?.value); // 18
console.log("Height:", numTree.height());      // 2
console.log("Size:",   numTree.size());        // 7

// Delete a leaf
numTree.delete(3);
console.log("After deleting 3:", numTree.inorder()); // [5, 7, 10, 12, 15, 18]

// Delete a node with one child
numTree.delete(5);
console.log("After deleting 5:", numTree.inorder()); // [7, 10, 12, 15, 18]

// Delete a node with two children
numTree.delete(15);
console.log("After deleting 15:", numTree.inorder()); // [7, 10, 12, 18]

// --- String BST ---
const strTree = new BinarySearchTree<string>();
strTree.insert("banana").insert("apple").insert("cherry").insert("date");
console.log("String BST inorder:", strTree.inorder()); // ["apple", "banana", "cherry", "date"]

// --- Custom Object BST (with comparator) ---
interface Person {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

const personTree = new BinarySearchTree<Person>(
  (a, b) => a.age - b.age // sort by age
);

personTree.insert({ name: "Alice", age: 30 });
personTree.insert({ name: "Bob",   age: 25 });
personTree.insert({ name: "Carol", age: 35 });

console.log(
  "People by age:",
  personTree.inorder().map((p) => `${p.name}(${p.age})`)
); // ["Bob(25)", "Alice(30)", "Carol(35)"]
```

---

Here is a breakdown of the key design decisions:

**Generic with a custom comparator**
The class is `BinarySearchTree<T>`, so it works with numbers, strings, or any custom object. A default comparator handles primitives automatically; pass a custom one for complex types.

**Delete uses the in-order successor strategy**
When deleting a node with two children, it finds the smallest node in the right subtree (in-order successor), copies its value up, then deletes the successor — this preserves BST ordering with minimal restructuring.

**Method chaining**
`insert` and `delete` return `this`, so you can chain calls like `bst.insert(1).insert(2).delete(1)`.

**All three traversals included**
- `inorder` (L → Root → R): produces sorted output, the most commonly needed
- `preorder` (Root → L → R): useful for serialization/cloning
- `postorder` (L → R → Root): useful for safe deletion or expression evaluation

**Time complexities**

| Method | Average | Worst (skewed tree) |
|---|---|---|
| `insert` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `search` / `contains` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `delete` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `inorder` / `preorder` / `postorder` | O(n) | O(n) |
| `findMin` / `findMax` | O(log n) | O(n) |
| `height` / `size` | O(n) | O(n) |

If you need guaranteed O(log n) performance regardless of insertion order, consider extending this into a self-balancing tree like an AVL or Red-Black tree.

